using System;

public class PrimeChecker {
    public static bool IsPrime(int number) {
        if (number < 2) {
            return false;
        }
        for (int i = 2; i <= Math.Sqrt(number); i++) {
            if (number % i == 0) {
                return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }

    public static void Main() {
        int number = 17;
        if (IsPrime(number)) {
            Console.WriteLine(number + " is prime.");
        } else {
            Console.WriteLine(number + " is not prime.");
        }
    }
}
```

In this program, we define a static method called `IsPrime` that takes an integer as input and returns a boolean value indicating whether the input number is prime. 

The `IsPrime` method first checks if the input number is less than 2, in which case it returns `false` since 0 and 1 are not prime. 

Next, the method loops through all numbers from 2 to the square root of the input number. For each number `i`, it checks if the input number is divisible by `i`. If it is, then the input number is not prime and the method returns `false`. 

If the method completes the loop without finding any divisors, then the input number is prime and the method returns `true`.

Finally, in the `Main` method, we call the `IsPrime` method with the integer value of 17 and print the result to the console. You can modify the value of `number` to check if other integers are prime or not.

